# Homey frontend standards

## Core philosophy

Homey frontend should feel:

- Warm
- Minimal
- Trustworthy
- International-student friendly
- Clean and modern
- Calm and welcoming

Avoid:

- Corporate banking style
- Overly playful cartoon UI
- Over-designed flashy animations
- Heavy visual clutter

---

# Design system

## Theme source of truth

- Follow the global theme defined in:
  - `frontend/app/globals.css`
  - `frontend/tailwind.config.ts`

- Use semantic Tailwind tokens instead of hardcoded colors.

## UI style rules

- Use soft shadows.
- Prefer rounded-2xl cards and inputs.
- Use generous whitespace and spacing.
- Avoid sharp corners unless intentionally minimal.
- Keep layouts visually calm and breathable.
- Prefer subtle hover effects.
- Avoid excessive gradients or neon colors.

## Typography

- Prioritize readability.
- Use clear font hierarchy.
- Keep headings visually strong but not oversized.
- Avoid dense text blocks.

---

# Responsive design

## Mobile-first required

All pages must be mobile-first responsive.

Use responsive Tailwind patterns:

```tsx
sm:grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3
```

## Layout rules

- Cards stack vertically on mobile.
- Avoid fixed widths that break small screens.
- Use max-width containers.
- Use consistent horizontal padding.

Preferred layout pattern:

```tsx
<div className="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
```

## Navigation

- Desktop navbar may collapse into mobile menu.
- Avoid overcrowded navigation.
- Mobile interactions should remain simple and touch-friendly.

---

# Components

## Keep components small and composable

Avoid large components.

If a component grows past ~200–300 lines:

- Extract presentational UI
- Extract hooks
- Extract reusable logic
- Split feature sections

## Pages are composition only

`frontend/src/app/**/page.tsx` should mainly:

- Read route params
- Fetch data
- Call hooks/stores
- Compose feature components
- Handle route-level loading/error states

Avoid large business logic inside pages.

## Component structure

Reusable UI:

```txt
frontend/src/components/ui/*
frontend/src/components/common/*
```

Feature-specific UI:

```txt
frontend/src/components/<feature>/*
```

Layout primitives:

```txt
frontend/src/components/layout/*
```

Examples:

```txt
Navbar
Sidebar
PageContainer
DashboardLayout
```

---

# Data access

## API calls

All HTTP calls must live in:

```txt
frontend/src/lib/api/*
```

Do not call axios/fetch directly inside components or pages.

Bad:

```tsx
const res = await axios.get(...)
```

Good:

```tsx
const listings = await getListings();
```

## Types

All API functions should return typed results.

Shared types belong in:

```txt
frontend/src/types/*
```

Avoid using `any`.

---

# Imports

Prefer absolute imports using:

```ts
@/
```

Avoid deep relative imports like:

```txt
../../../../
```

---

# State management

## General philosophy

- Prefer local state first.
- Use Zustand only when state is shared across multiple routes/components.
- Avoid unnecessary global state.

## Use local React state for:

- Form inputs
- Modal open/close
- Dropdowns
- Hover state
- Tabs
- Page-only filters
- Pagination
- Temporary UI state

Example:

```tsx
const [open, setOpen] = useState(false);
```

## Use Zustand for:

- Authentication state
- Current user
- Login status
- Role-based UI
- Global sidebar state
- Global notifications
- Cross-page favourites
- Chat session state (future)
- Unread counts (future)

## Store organization

Stores must stay domain-scoped.

Good:

```txt
authStore.ts
uiStore.ts
favouritesStore.ts
chatStore.ts
```

Bad:

```txt
appStore.ts containing everything
```

## Auth store rules

Preferred location:

```txt
frontend/src/lib/stores/authStore.ts
```

Example state:

```ts
user: User | null;
isAuthenticated: boolean;
isLoading: boolean;

setUser();
clearUser();
logout();
```

Rules:

- Do not store passwords.
- Do not store sensitive auth secrets.
- Backend session remains the source of truth.
- Zustand only mirrors lightweight frontend auth state.
- Re-fetch session via `/auth/me` when needed.

## Selectors

Prefer selectors to reduce re-renders.

Good:

```ts
const user = useAuthStore((state) => state.user);
```

Avoid:

```ts
const auth = useAuthStore();
```

unless necessary.

---

# Server state

Zustand is NOT the backend database.

Do not store:

- Large datasets
- Full listing collections
- Entire admin dashboards
- Massive API responses

Backend APIs remain the source of truth.

---

# Role-based UI

Frontend role checks are for UI only.

Backend must still enforce permissions.

Examples:

- Tenant → saved listings
- Landlord → create listing
- Admin → moderation dashboard

---

# Styling

## Tailwind only

Use Tailwind CSS consistently.

Avoid inline styles unless necessary.

## Consistency

Reuse spacing/layout patterns.

Avoid random padding/margin values.

Prefer shared UI primitives instead of duplicated layouts.

---

# Accessibility

- Buttons must have labels.
- Inputs must have labels.
- Forms should show validation errors clearly.
- Interactive elements need visible focus states.
- Avoid relying only on color to communicate meaning.

---

# Animations

- Keep animations subtle and purposeful.
- Prefer simple transitions.
- Avoid excessive motion.

Good:

```txt
hover shadow
fade in
slide transition
```

Avoid:

```txt
heavy bouncing
complex parallax
aggressive motion
```

---

# Quality checks

Before review:

```bash
npm run lint
npm run test
```

## Testing

Add/update tests when behavior changes.

Use:

- Unit tests
- Component tests
- Storybook stories where useful

---

# Performance

- Avoid unnecessary re-renders.
- Lazy load heavy components when appropriate.
- Keep client components minimal.
- Prefer server components where possible in Next.js App Router.

---

# Code quality

- Prefer readable code over clever code.
- Keep files focused.
- Avoid deeply nested JSX.
- Prefer explicit naming.
- Use TypeScript properly.

Code should be easy for another engineer to understand quickly.

